# 🔥 1. What is Abstraction?

From your notes:

> **Showing essential details and hiding background implementation**

---

## ✅ Simple Meaning

You only see **WHAT to do**, not **HOW it is done**

---

## 🔹 Examples (from your notes)

* Electric switch → you press, light turns ON (you don’t know wiring)
* ATM → withdraw money (you don’t know backend logic)
* Car → drive (you don’t know engine internals)

---

# 🔥 2. How Abstraction is Achieved in Java?

From your notes:

### ✔ 1) Abstract Class → Partial Abstraction

### ✔ 2) Interface → Full Abstraction

---

# 🔥 3. Abstract Method (VERY IMPORTANT)

From your notes:

```java
public abstract void play();
```

---

## ✅ Rules

* No method body ❌
* Ends with `;`
* Must use `abstract` keyword

---

## 🔥 Meaning

> “I am declaring the method, but someone else will define it”

---

# 🔥 4. Abstract Class

From your notes:

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    public abstract void run();
}
```

---

## ✅ Rules

* If a class has **at least one abstract method → class must be abstract**
* Cannot create object of abstract class ❌

```java
Vehicle v = new Vehicle(); ❌ ERROR
```

---

## ✅ Can contain:

* Abstract methods ✔
* Concrete methods ✔
* Variables ✔

---

# 🔥 5. Why Abstract Class?

👉 To provide **common structure + partial implementation**

---

## 🔹 Example

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    abstract void run();   // no body

    void fuel() {          // body present
        System.out.println("Fuel needed");
    }
}
```

---

# 🔥 6. Who gives implementation?

👉 Child class

```java
class Car extends Vehicle {
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Car is running");
    }
}
```

---

# 🔥 7. Interface (Full Abstraction)

From your notes:

> Interface = 100% abstraction

---

## 🔹 Example

```java
interface Vehicle {
    void run();
}
```

---

## ✅ Rules

* All methods are **abstract by default**
* No method body (in basic understanding)
* Class must use `implements`

---

## 🔹 Implementation

```java
class Car implements Vehicle {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Car running");
    }
}
```

---

# 🔥 8. Difference: Abstract Class vs Interface

| Feature         | Abstract Class      | Interface                   |
| --------------- | ------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Abstraction     | Partial             | Full                        |
| Methods         | Abstract + Concrete | Only abstract (basic level) |
| Keyword         | `extends`           | `implements`                |
| Object creation | ❌                   | ❌                           |

---

# 🔥 9. Real Concept (VERY IMPORTANT)

### 👉 Abstract Class = “Incomplete class”

### 👉 Interface = “Contract”

---

## 🔹 Contract Meaning

```java
interface Printable {
    void print();
}
```

👉 Any class using it MUST implement `print()`

---

# 🔥 10. Final Flow (Important)

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    abstract void run();
}

class Bike extends Vehicle {
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Bike running");
    }
}
```

---

# 🔥 11. Key Points to Remember

* Abstract method → no body
* Abstract class → cannot be instantiated
* Child class must implement abstract methods
* Interface → full abstraction (basic understanding)

---

# 🔴 Final One-line Memory

> Abstraction = **Hide implementation, show only functionality**

